<chapter id="options">
 <title>Internal Configuration</title>
 <para>
  This section details configuration options available through the
  <guimenu>Options</guimenu> menu.  For external configuration options
  including command-line options and configuration files, see the
  <link linkend="manpages">options and configuration reference</link>.
 </para>

 <sect1 id="options-display">
  <title>Display Options</title>

  <para>
   The following options are available through the
   <menuchoice>
    <guimenu>Options</guimenu>
    <guisubmenu>Display</guisubmenu>
   </menuchoice>
   menu.
  </para>

  <glosslist>
   <glossentry>
    <glossterm>Automatic Window Docking</glossterm>
    <glossdef><para>
     This option can be toggled on or off.  When off, any new packet
     panes (created when you view or edit a packet) will be opened in
     separate floating windows.  When on, new packet panes will be
     docked into the main &regina; window if possible.
    </para></glossdef>
   </glossentry>

   <glossentry>
    <glossterm>Display Icon</glossterm>
    <glossdef><para>
     This option can be toggled on or off; it represents whether the
     large &regina; icon will be displayed beneath the packet tree in
     the main window.
    </para></glossdef>
   </glossentry>
  </glosslist>
 </sect1>

 <sect1 id="options-file">
  <title>File Options</title>

  <para>
   The following options are available through the
   <menuchoice>
    <guimenu>Options</guimenu>
    <guisubmenu>File</guisubmenu>
   </menuchoice>
   menu.
  </para>

  <glosslist>
   <glossentry>
    <glossterm>Automatic File Extension</glossterm>
    <glossdef><para>
     This option can be toggled on or off; it represents whether a
     filename is modified before a &regina; data file is saved.
     When on, if the user does not specify a filename extension, the
     default extension of <filename>.rga</filename> will be appended.
    </para></glossdef>
   </glossentry>
  </glosslist>
 </sect1>

 <sect1 id="options-help">
  <title>Help Browser Options</title>

  <para>
   The
   <menuchoice>
    <guimenu>Options</guimenu>
    <guisubmenu>Help Browser</guisubmenu>
   </menuchoice>
   menu item allows the user to set a preferred method for browsing
   documentation from within &regina;, such as when
   <menuchoice>
    <guimenu>Help</guimenu>
    <guimenuitem>Contents</guimenuitem>
   </menuchoice>
   is selected.  Documentation can be browsed in
   one of the two ways described below.
  </para>
  <tip><para>
   Using an external web browser is recommended, since &javahelp; (as of
   the time of writing this document) does not render pages very well at
   all.
  </para></tip>

  <glosslist>
   <glossentry>
    <glossterm>Internal &javahelp; browser</glossterm>
    <glossdef>
     <para>
      This method uses &javahelp;, an embedded help browser
      provided by &javasoft;.  Using &javahelp; is the default, although
      this method is not recommended (see above).
     </para>
     <para>
      To select this method, simply check the
      <guilabel>JavaHelp</guilabel> checkbox in the <guilabel>Help
      Browser</guilabel> dialog.
     </para>
     <para>
      You will need to ensure that the &javahelp; jar
      (<filename>jh.jar</filename>) and the documentation jar
      (<filename>regina-docs.jar</filename>) are both available.
      The &helpabout; box will tell you whether these jars can be
      found, and starting &regina; with the <option>--verbose</option>
      option will show you where it is currently looking for these jars.
      If necessary, the locations of these jars can be set in the
      <link linkend="man-regina.conf">configuration files</link>.
     </para>
     <para>
      Instructions for downloading &javahelp; can be found at the
      <ulink url="http://regina.sourceforge.net/sysreq.html">&regina;
      website</ulink>.
     </para>
    </glossdef>
   </glossentry>
   <glossentry>
    <glossterm>External web browser</glossterm>
    <glossdef>
     <para>
      This method uses your favourite web browser to view the
      documentation.  You will need the documentation fully unpacked
      somewhere on your system, but neither <filename>jh.jar</filename>
      nor <filename>regina-docs.jar</filename> will be required.  This
      method is the recommended choice (see above).
     </para>
     <para>
      To select this method, you will need to uncheck the
      <guilabel>JavaHelp</guilabel> checkbox in the <guilabel>Help
      Browser</guilabel> dialog.  In the <guilabel>command</guilabel>
      box you will need to type the command that starts your web browser
      (such as <command>/usr/bin/konqueror</command> or
      <command>c:\netscape\netscape.exe</command>).  In the
      <guilabel>location</guilabel> box you will need to type the
      directory containing the documentation &html; files such as
      <filename>index.html</filename> and
      <filename>welcome.html</filename>.  For instance, if the
      documentation index is
      <filename>/usr/share/regina/docs/index.html</filename>, the
      <guilabel>location</guilabel> box should contain
      <filename>/usr/share/regina/docs</filename>.
     </para>
     <para>
      Note that instead of unpacking the documentation on your system,
      you may choose to refer to the online documentation at the &regina;
      website.  In this case, the <guilabel>location</guilabel> box
      should contain an appropriate &url; such as
      <filename>http://regina.sourceforge.net/docs</filename>.
     </para>
    </glossdef>
   </glossentry>
  </glosslist>
 </sect1>

 <sect1 id="options-libraries">
  <title>&jython; Library Options</title>

  <para>
   &jython; libraries are files containing
   &jython; code to run at the beginning of every &jython;
   session, including every time a &jython; console is opened and
   every time a script packet is run.  See the
   <link linkend="jython-overview">&jython; scripting overview</link>
   for further details.
  </para>

  <para>
   The
   <menuchoice>
    <guimenu>Options</guimenu>
    <guisubmenu>Jython Libraries</guisubmenu>
   </menuchoice>
   menu item opens a list of &jython; libraries that &regina; currently
   knows about.  Beside each library is a checkbox labelled
   <guilabel>Use</guilabel>.  Only the libraries whose
   <guilabel>Use</guilabel> boxes are checked will be loaded at the
   beginning of each &jython; session.  Thus by unchecking its
   <guilabel>Use</guilabel> box you can disable a library but still have
   &regina; remember its location.
  </para>

  <para>
   Each library also has a <guibutton>Compile</guibutton> button beside
   it.  Pressing this button will test whether or not the library
   actually compiles under &jython;.  The library code will only be
   compiled; it will not be run.
  </para>
 </sect1>

 <sect1 id="options-plaf">
  <title>Look and Feel Options</title>

  <para>
   The 
   <menuchoice>
    <guimenu>Options</guimenu>
    <guisubmenu>Look and Feel</guisubmenu>
   </menuchoice>
   menu contains a list of
   &java; look-and-feels that are available on your system.  The
   look-and-feel determines the way that basic elements of the &gui;
   such as buttons, menus, windows and the like are displayed.
   To try a different look-and-feel, select the appropriate
   option from this menu.
  </para>
 </sect1>
</chapter>
